<subSubSection id="842625A622B342F8EB7C3DA422178331" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" type="comments">
<paragraph id="94086C7B13D946E65116CD8157C9CBEE" pageId="21" pageNumber="52">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3612C139E082CE41592D072CB8FCF2B0" pageId="21" pageNumber="52">
<taxonomicName id="1A36024D8DA094B774006D6C7BDFDA99" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile cleomis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cleomis">Megachile cleomis</taxonomicName>
is one of the synonyms of 
<taxonomicName id="82203A68029D7C0B2FCF341C2CFD1912" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile texana" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="texana">Megachile texana</taxonomicName>
. It was originally described by Cockerell in 
<bibRefCitation id="F82A4043F84E57EBBB33CBD08530421C" author="Cockerell, TDA" journalOrPublisher="The Annals and Magazine of Natural History" pageId="22" pageNumber="53" pagination="13 - 15" title="The New Mexico bees of the Genus Megachile and a new Andrena." volume="6" year="1900">1900</bibRefCitation>
, based on two cotypes from a locality in New Mexico, a male and a female. The male was later found to be a male 
<taxonomicName id="EE43016BDB2A8204D9D6E714E54D337D" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile snowi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="snowi">Megachile snowi</taxonomicName>
. The female is herein designated as the lectotype for 
<taxonomicName id="29CF6528D5A3F37CD0B486394C78BBB7" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile cleomis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cleomis">Megachile cleomis</taxonomicName>
, which remains in synonymy with 
<taxonomicName id="2177F47A77C2E0B50EC1D6BBDE3C39DF" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile texana" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="texana">Megachile texana</taxonomicName>
. This situation illustrates the importance of correctly assigning holotypes. 
<taxonomicName id="B1EDB424B0F2146B970AF3384D4E133F" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile texana" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="texana">Megachile texana</taxonomicName>
is a widespread species which is found across North America (Figure 17).
</paragraph>
